Chem. 10.1002/ange.201814172 First Total Synthesis of Actinorhodin  Mamiko Ninomiya, Yoshio Ando, Fumitaka Kudo, Ken Ohmori,* and Keisuke Suzuki*  Dedicated to Professor Dr. Axel Zeeck Abstract:  The  enantioselective  first  total  synthesis  of  actinorhodin  (1) is described, featuring (1) dual benzyne reactions en route to the  monomer,  (2)  trans-selective  installation  of  the  side  chain,  and  (3)  the regioselective oxidative dimerization.

Actinorhodin  (1)  is  a  red  pigment  isolated  in  1947  from  Streptomyces  coelicolor  A3(2)  by  Brockmann  et  al.[1]  and  historically  the  oldest  pyranonaphthoquinone  antibiotic  (Figure  1).[2]  As  a  representative  type-II  polyketide  metabolite,[3]  the  structure of 1 appears in many books.[4] Surprisingly, however, no  NMR data of 1  has been recorded, presumably due to its extreme  insolubility  (vide  infra).  Thus,  the  structure  of  1,  including  the  relative  and  absolute  stereochemistries,  was  assigned  on  the  chemical  bases  by  Brockmann  and  Zeeck,[5,6]  and  the  position  of  the  biaryl  bond  was  determined  by  the  biosynthetic  study  by  Floss.[6h]  At  first  glance,  the  structure  of  1  appears  to  be  a  dimer  of  nanaomycin A,[7] a representative monomer of this class. In reality,  however, there are two significant distinctions, (1) the monomeric  unit  is  enantiomeric  (n.B.,  ent-nanaomycin  A  is  also  a  natural  product),[8]  and  (2)  additional  hydroxy  groups  at  C6  and  C6’  are  present, conforming to binaphthazarin.  Figure 1. Pyranonaphthoquinones.

While  numerous  syntheses  of  the  related  monomers  have  been  reported,[9–12]  the  dimer  synthesis  is  far  more  challenging,[13]  and  the  only  example  of  the  completed  synthesis  has  been  the  recent  report on the total synthesis of a kalafungin-related, more oxidized  dimer, g-actinorhodin by Brückner.[14]   In  connection  with  our  synthetic  interest  in  dimeric  natural  Ms. Mamiko Ninomiya, Dr. Yoshio Ando, Prof. Dr. Fumitaka Kudo,  Prof. Dr. Ken Ohmori, Prof. Dr. Keisuke Suzuki  Department of Chemistry, Tokyo Institute of Technology  2-12-1 O-okayama, Meguro-ku, Tokyo 152-8551 (Japan)  Fax: (+81) 3-5734-2788   E-mail: ksuzuki@chem.titech.ac.jp; kohmori@chem.titech.ac.jp  Supporting information\ is available on the WWW under  http://dx.doi.org/10.1002/anie.2014 xxxxxx.

products,[15]  we  embarked  on  the  total  synthesis  of  1,  keeping  in  mind  three  synthetic  issues  shown  in  a  retrosynthetic  fashion  in  Figure 2. Issue 1 is the regiocontrol of the dimerization, a challenge,  given  the  high  symmetry  around  the  reaction  sites.  Assuming  a  solution  resorting  to  a  directing-effect  of  free  phenols,[9a,16]  the  second task is to install multiple oxy-functions in a discriminating  fashion,  so  that  the  free  phenols  are  at  our  disposal  at  the  dimerization stage. The third issue is rigorous stereocontrol in both  enantio-  and  diastereomeric  senses  in  the  preparation  of  the  monomer.  However,  seemingly-simple  stereocontrol  of  the  1,3- trans-relationship  has  not  been  established:[17]  The  often-used  strategy  is  acid-mediated  equilibration  (Figure  2b),[10,11a,b,d–k,12a,b,d– g]  which  only  gives  imperfect  cis/trans-ratio,  inevitably  requiring  isomer separation.   Figure 2. Synthetic challenges to 1 and acid isomerization of monomer.  Herein,  we  describe  the  first  enantioselective  total  synthesis  of  1,  based  on  the  retrosynthetic  analysis  shown  in  Scheme  1.  The  1H  NMR  data  of  1,  not  previously  reported  due  to  its  extreme  insolubility, is now recorded.  Scheme 1. COMMUNICATION  The dimer 1 can be disconnected into the two identical monomers  A. The hope was that the unprotected phenols would allow the site- selective  oxidative  coupling  of  A  at  C8–C8’;[9a,16] we  had  a  good  experience with this approach in another project.[15a] Naphthazarin  A  would  in  turn  be  derived  from  naphthalenediol  derivative  B  by  regioselective  adjusting  manipulations would hopefully be possible by selective protection  of the phenolic functions. The side chain in B would be installed by  using  lactol  C  as  the  precursor,  and  the  Lewis  acid-mediated  activation  followed  by  attack  of  p-nucleophile  would  allow  the  desired  trans-selective  reaction  under  kinetic  control.[18]  The  stereocenter in alcohol D would be established by enantioselective  reduction  of  ketone  E.  Finally,  naphthyl  ketoester  E,  a  penta- substituted  benzene,  would  be  assembled  by  dual  benzyne  reactions.[19]  Bis-sulfonate  2  would  work  as  a  1,4-benzdiyne  equivalent[20] to allow stepwise generations of two benzyne species,  reacting  with  furan  (F)  and  methyl  acetoacetate  (G),  respectively.  The  two  different  functional  arrays,  iodo–tosylate[21]  and  silyl– triflate,[22]  in  2  would  allow  chemoselective  generation  of  two  different benzyne species.   With this plan in mind, our synthetic study began with preparation  of the 1,4-benzdiyne equivalent 2 from pyrogallol (3) (Scheme 2).  Following  a  literature  procedure  with  slight  modification,[23]  the  central hydroxy group in 3 was selectively benzylated, giving ether  4  in  46%  yield.  Iodination  of  4

(3) (Scheme 2).  Following  a  literature  procedure  with  slight  modification,[23]  the  central hydroxy group in 3 was selectively benzylated, giving ether  4  in  46%  yield.  Iodination  of  4  with  NIS  in  the  presence  of  a  catalytic  amount  of  TfOH  with  careful  control  of  the  temperature  gave diiodide 5 in 90% yield.[24] Conversion of 5 into silyl triflate 2  was executed by a one-pot procedure: silylation of the phenols in 5  with (Me3Si)2NH followed by the retro-Brook rearrangement[25] of  H by treatment with nBuLi at –95 °C gave phenoxide I, which was  immediately  trapped  by  Tf2O.  After  quenching  by  addition  of  Et2NH to consume the unreacted Tf2O, the resulting phenol 6  was  tosylated to give 2 in 79% yield in 4 steps.

Scheme 2. Synthesis of 1,4-benzdiyne equivalent. a) BnBr (1.0 equiv), K2CO3  (1.0 equiv), acetone, 18 h (46%). b) NIS (3.0 equiv), TfOH (0.2 equiv), CH2Cl2,  –78 ® –60 °C, 3 h (90%). c) (Me3Si)2NH (3.0 equiv), THF, 3 h. d) nBuLi (1.0  equiv),  THF,  –95  °C,  10  min.  e)  Tf2O  (1.1  equiv);  Et2NH  (0.2  equiv).  f)  TsCl  (1.5 equiv), K2CO3 (2.0 equiv), DMF, –95 °C ® RT, 13 h (79% for 4 steps). Bn  = benzyl, NIS = N-iodosuccinimide, TfOH = trifluoromethanesulfonic acid, Tf2O  =  trifluoromethanesulfonic  anhydride,  Ts  =  p-toluenesulfonyl,  DMF  =  N,  N- dimethylformamide.

With  1,4-benzdiyne  equivalent  2  in  hand,  we  embarked  on  the  synthetic endeavor, starting with the first benzyne generation in the  presence of furan (7) as the arynophile (Scheme 3). Treatment of 2  with  nBuLi  at  –78  °C  in  the  presence  of  an  excess  amount  of  7  allowed  the  benzyne  generation  and  [4+2]  cycloaddition,  giving  cycloadduct  8  in  91%  yield.  It  should  be  noted  that,  without  any  obvious  reasons,  cycloadduct  8  was  potentially  explosive  when  condensed  to  a  neat  solid,  and  should  be  kept  as  a  solution  in  organic solvent. The second benzyne species was generated from 8  in the presence of methyl acetoacetate (9), using KF and 18-crown- 6  (THF,  18  h,  room  temperature)  –  in  which  diluted  conditions  (0.02 M) were critical – giving keto ester 10 in 53% yield.[26] The  regioselectivity  is  derived  from  the  benzyloxy  group  as  in  J.  An  ensuing attack of the benzene anion on the ketone moiety leads to  the oxy-anion substituted benzocyclobutene K,[27] which undergoes  a ring opening by a retro-aldolization, providing ketoester 10.[28]  Scheme  3.  Dual  benzyne  reactions.  a)  nBuLi  (1.2  equiv),  THF,  –78  °C,  6  h  (91%). b) KF (3.0 equiv), 18-crown-6 (3.0 equiv), toluene, THF (0.02 M), 18 h  (53%).

Next, the asymmetric reduction of ketone 10 was attempted (Table  1). Although ketone 10 was a racemic mixture, we chose a reagent- controlled  approach,  assuming  that  the  pre-existing  stereogenic  centers are far enough from the reaction site, and would not affect,  if any, the asymmetric induction process.  As the first attempt, Noyori reduction[29] was examined, which only  gave  partial  recovery  of  the  starting  material  10  (entry  1).  By  reduction[30]  produced  many  contrast,  unidentified  byproducts,  which  we  ascribed  to  the  competing  hydroboration of the C=C bond in 10.   This  notion  led  us  to  an  idea  of  using  equimolar  amounts  of  the  CBS reagent and BH3. The hope was that pre-coordinated complex  L[30b]  would  be  responsible  only  for  the  carbonyl  reduction,  not  affecting  the  olefin.  Thus,  to  a  chilled  (–78  °C)  THF  solution  of  ketoester  10  and  CBS  reagent  (2.0  equiv)  was  carefully  added  BH3·THF (2.0 equiv); further stirring at –50 °C for 22 h gave lactol  11 in 69% yield and diol 12 in 24% yield.[31]	   Table 1. Once correct stereochemistry was confirmed, we moved on to the  introduction  of  the  side  chain  into  lactol  11  (Scheme  5).  To  a  chilled solution of 11 and allyltrimethylsilane in CH2Cl2 at –78 °C  was  added  TMSOTf,  where  the  substitution  by  an  allyl  group  (OH→CH2CH=CH2) and aromatization proceeded simultaneously,  giving  pyranonaphthol  14  as  a  single  diastereomer.[18]  The  trans  relationship  of  the  two  substituents,  methyl  and  allyl,  was  established  by  NOE  analysis.  The  stereochemical  outcome  could  be  explained  by  considering  the  allylic  strain  in  oxonium  species  M, in which the diastereotopic faces are well discriminated.[33]  Two  additional  notes:  (1)  Opening  of  the  1,4-epoxide  in  11  proceeded  regioselectively,  as  rationalized  by  the  directing  effect  of benzyloxy group,[34] (2) The ee of 14 was assessed to be >99%  by HPLC analysis on chiral stationary phase,[35] an additional data  for the perfect selectivity in the CBS-reduction, 10®11, vide supra.  [36]  in  aq.  1,4-dioxane  in  the  Oxidation  of  14  with  PhI(OCOCF3)2 dark[37]  followed  by  treatment  of  the  resulting  p-quinone  with  aqueous  Na2S2O4  gave  air-sensitive  hydroquinone  15,  which,  without purification, was immediately treated with (MeO)2SO2 and  K2CO3, giving the dimerization precursor  16 in 58% overall yield  (3  steps). At  this  stage,  a  small  amount  of  the  corresponding  dimethyl  ether  17  was  obtained  (13%  yield).[38]  Preferential  methylation  at  the  C6  hydroxy  group  was  a  desired  outcome,  as  expected by its higher reactivity in comparison to the C9 hydroxy  group  that  has  a  hydrogen  bonding  with  proximal  benzyloxy  group.[39]

Synthesis  of  dimerization  precursor.  a)  allyltrimethylsilane  (10.0  equiv),  Me3SiOTf  (1.0  equiv),  CH2Cl2,  –78  °C,  15  min  (76%,  >99%  ee).  b)  PhI(OCOCF3)2 (2.5 equiv), H2O, 1,4-dioxane, acetone, 0 °C, 3 h; Na2S2O4 aq.  c) (MeO)2SO2 (1.2 equiv), K2CO3 (1.5 equiv), acetone, reflux, 5.5 h.  The  stage  was  set  for  the  dimerization  of  naphthol  16  with  a  free  C9-hydroxy  group  (Scheme  6).  To  our  delight,  exposure  of  16  to  Laatsch’s conditions (Ag2O, Et3N) [9a] smoothly gave quinoid 18 as  a  dark  navy-blue  solid,  which  was  reduced  with  Zn  to  give  colorless pyranonaphthol 19 in excellent yield. The regioselectivity  of  dimerization  at  C8–C8’  was  evidenced  by  extensive  2D  NMR  analysis of 19. Protection of the resulting phenols by methyl groups  gave dimer 20 in quantitative yield.  Scheme 6. Oxidative dimerization. a) Ag2O (1.8 equiv), Et3N (0.64 equiv),  CH2Cl2, RT, 2 h. b) Zn (4.0 equiv), AcOH, CHCl3, RT, 1 h (96% for 2 steps). c)  (MeO)2SO2, NaH, DMF, 0 °C, 1.5 h (quant).

Scheme 7 shows the endgame of the synthesis. The terminal olefins  in  dimer  20  were  cleaved  by  Lemieux–Johnson  oxidation,[40]  giving  the  corresponding  dialdehyde  21,  which  was  oxidized  to  dicarboxylic acid 22,[41] and further converted to diester 23 for the  ease  of  handling.  After  removal  of  the  benzyl  groups  by  hydrogenolysis, the resulting naphthol 24 was oxidized with CAN,  giving  binaphthazarin  25.  The  methyl  protecting  groups  for  the  phenols in 25 were removed by exposure to MgI2·OEt2 (50 equiv,  Et2O,  MeCN,  room  temperature),[42]  providing  binaphthazarin  26  as  a  purple  red  solid.  No  isomerization  into  the  cis-stereoisomer  was  observed  under  these  conditions.  Saponification  of  26  with  LiOH·H2O,  and  acidification  by  DOWEX®  (H+  form)  gave  the  final product 1.   21: R = CHO 22: R = COOH 23: R = COOMe

The  reaction  mixture  showed  impressive  color  change.  Upon  treatment  of  26  with  the  base,  the  color  quickly  changed  from  purple red to blue, which turned into purple red upon acidification  (see  I→II→III  in  Scheme  7).  Such  pH-chromic  behavior  is  characteristic to naphthazarin derivatives.[43]  The  crude  material  of  1  contained  small  amounts  of  impurities  (assessed  by  1H  NMR).  Reprecipitation  from  1,4-dioxane  gave  pure  1  as  a  purple  red  solid,  which  became  further  insoluble.  It  should  be  noted  that  the  solubility  of  1  to  various  solvents  was  extremely poor.[1] The peaks in  1H NMR spectrum of pure 1 were  weaker in magnitude than the satellite peaks of the solvent (THF- d8)  (Figure  3a).  Since,  in  the  1H  NMR  spectrum  of  synthetic  1,  unidentified  impurities  come  from  distilled  THF-d8  were  included  (Figure 3b), the 1H NMR spectrum of blank THF-d8 was subtracted  from the 1H NMR spectrum of synthetic 1, giving a clear spectrum  as shown in Figure 3c.  Figure 3. 1H NMR spectra (600 MHz, THF-d8, 13.2–1.4 ppm); a) synthetic 1,   b) blank THF-d8, c) differential spectrum of synthetic 1 (a–b).

As  the  1H  NMR  spectra  of  the  natural  product  had  not  been  reported,  we  conducted  fermentation  of  Streptomyces  coelicolor  A3(2)  in  our  lab  and  isolated  an  authentic  sample  of  1  according  to  the  literature  procedure.[44]  Upon  direct  comparison,  the  1H NMR spectra of the synthetic and authentic specimen fully  coincided.  Due  to  the  low  solubility  of  1  in  various  solvents,  comparison  of  the  CD  spectra  was  done  after  conversion  into  diester  26  (Figure  4).  The  CD  curve  of  synthetic  26  was  superimposable  with  that  of  26  derived  from  the  natural  sample,  giving  an  independent  validation  of  the  absolute  configuration  of  1.[45]  Figure  4. CD spectra of actinorhodin dimethyl ester (in CHCl3): synthetic  sample 26 (left) and sample derived from natural actinorhodin (right).  In  summary,  total  synthesis  of  first  enantioselective  actinorhodin  (1)  has  been  achieved,  featuring  use  of  benzdiyne  equivalent  as  a  precursor  for  the  pyranonaphthoquinone  structure.  CD (26 from natural actinorhodin) Further  efforts  to  synthesize  other  dimeric  pyranonaphthoquinone  antibiotics are currently underway in our laboratory.
